# Risk of an estimator

An estimation problem is defined by a parameter space `Оҳ`, a data generating kernel `P : Kernel Оҳ рқ“§`
and a loss function `в„“ : Оҳ вҶ’ рқ“Ё вҶ’ в„қвүҘ0вҲһ`.
A (randomized) estimator is a kernel `Оә : Kernel рқ“§ рқ“Ё` that maps data to estimates of a quantity
of interest that depends on the parameter. Often the quantity of interest is the parameter itself
and `рқ“Ё = Оҳ`.
The quality of an estimate `y` when data comes from the distribution with parameter `Оё` is measured
by the value of the loss function `в„“ Оё y` (lower is better).

## Main definitions

The risk is the average loss of the estimator `Оә` on data generated by `P` with parameter `Оё`,
equal to `вҲ«вҒ» y, в„“ Оё y вҲӮ((Оә вҲҳвӮ– P) Оё)`. We do not introduce a definition for that risk, but we refer
to that integral as `risk` in lemma names.

* `avgRisk в„“ P Оә ПҖ`: the average of the risk of the estimator with respect to
  the prior `ПҖ : Measure Оҳ`.
* `bayesRisk в„“ P ПҖ`: the Bayes risk with respect to the prior `ПҖ`, minimum of the average
  risks over all estimators, that is over all Markov kernels `Оә : Kernel рқ“§ рқ“Ё`.
* `minimaxRisk в„“ P`: minimax risk, infimum over all estimators of the maximum over `Оё` of the risk.

